    "embed": "true",
    "long_instructions": "##  🔍Teacher Tip\r\n\r\nExplore the Character Quiz Widget students will use during <a href='https://studio.code.org/courses/exploring-gen-ai-2025/units/1/lessons/6' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer' style='text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;'>Lesson 6: Understanding Embeddings</a>.\r\n\r\nWhile you're using the Widget think about *how you'll have students transition between the parts of the activity*.\r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n# Character Quiz\r\n\r\n## Overview\r\n\r\nWe'll be completing a \"personality quiz\" as different characters, and then comparing them to see which characters are the most similar or most different. First you will complete the quiz as a character of your choice, then you'll move around the classroom to compare characters with your peers\r\n\r\n## Part 1\r\nIn this part, we fill out the quiz as our own character\r\n\r\n1) Choose a character you are familiar with to fill out this form. Write this person's name at the top of the widget.\r\n2) Click the number for each trait to place a mark on the scale to represent how your character aligns with each trait.\r\n3) Come up with two additional traits and add them to the bottom of the list. For example: \"Light\" vs \"Dark\".\r\n\r\nWhen you are finished, press the \"Ready for Part 2\" button\r\n\r\n## Part 2\r\nIn this part, other people fill out the quiz as their characters\r\n\r\n1) Leave your computer and visit someone else's quiz. Fill out the quiz as your character\r\n2) When you are finished filling out this quiz, press the \"Done! Next Character!\" button\r\n3) When you return to your original computer, press the \"Ready for Part 3!\" button\r\n\r\n## Part 3\r\nIn this part, you can compare your character with other characters from the class\r\n\r\n1) Look at the data you've collected. Each character is represented by a colored dot at the top. Your character is always red.\r\n2) Answer the following questions either on a piece of paper or with a neighbor:\r\n    - For each character: which traits are close together? Which traits are far apart?\r\n    - Which character overall do you think you are \"most similar\" to? \r\n    - Which character overall do you think you are \"most different\" from?\r\n  \r\n\r\n---\r\n\r\n##  🔍Teacher Tip\r\n\r\nAfter students complete the activity classroom discussions will help them to understand that they can compare numbers in each position to determine how similar or different characters are. One powerful insight is that it doesn’t matter what each position represents, only how close or far the numbers are in that same position.\r\n\r\nThese key concepts helps to generalize the idea of “character traits” to **embeddings**, the set of numbers used to represent a word in a large-language model.\r\n\r\n<p style=\"font-size: 18px; background-color: #F5F7F8; padding: 10px; border-left: 5px solid #8148B2; display: inline-block;\">\r\n    🚀 <b>Take it Futher:</b> There's an additional <i>optional</i> lesson on embeddings. Check out the <a href='https://studio.code.org/courses/exploring-gen-ai-2025/units/1/lessons/14' target='_blank' rel='noopener noreferrer' style='text-decoration: none; font-weight: bold;'>Lesson Plan</a> to determine whether or not you want to teach it.\r\n</p>\r\n",
